The relationship between education and salary **is** mediated by skill level! We have a significant indirect effect of 0.66, 95% CI [0.4, 0.93].  

The total effect of education on salary is 1.14, and the indirect effect is 0.66.  
$\frac{0.66}{1.14} = 0.58$, so 58% of the effect is mediated by the influence that education has on skillset and skillset has on salary. 




</div><p class="solution-end"></p>





<div class='question-begin'>Question 4</div><div class='question-body'>


Nothing to code here, just spend a little time to get to grips with what the different parts of the model represent:  

if you can, write down for explanation of each of:  

- a
- b
- the total effect
- the direct effect
- the indirect effect

![](images/path_educparts.png)




</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div class="solution-begin"><button id='sol-start-4' class="jk-circle-right solution-icon clickable" onclick="toggle_visibility('sol-body-4', 'sol-start-4')">  Solution </button></div><div class="solution-body" id = "sol-body-4" style="display: none;">



- **a: ** this is the estimated number of skills you acquire for every additional year of education. So each year of education tends to lead to acquiring 2.48 new skills.  

- **b: ** this is the estimated increase in salary for every additional skill you have, if you hold years of education constant. So if you just keep your years of education the same, but teach yourself an extra skill, we'd expect your salary to increase by £270  

- **the direct effect: ** this is the estimated increase in salary for every additional year of education, holding number of skills constant. Imagine that you didn't show up to any classes for your masters degree (and so you didn't learn any new skills), but we still gave you the certificate at the end. Having that bit of paper means we expect you to earn £480 more (compared to someone who has the same skill set as you but doesn't have the extra year of education).  

- **the total effect: ** this is the estimated increase in salary for every additional year of education. So by doing your masters degree, we'd expect your salary to be £1140 higher than someone without a masters degree. It will be higher partly because of the skills you acquire (the indirect effect) and partly because of just having the certificate (the direct effect)

- **the indirect effect: ** this is the estimated increase in salary due to the skills you tend to acquire for every additional year of education. To put this another way, imagine that during your masters degree, you come to classes and obtain the various skills that tend to be gained from a masters, but then you never get round to finishing, so you never get your certificate. We would expect your salary to be £659 higher than someone who didn't do the masters degree.  




</div><p class="solution-end"></p>







<div class='question-begin'>Question 5</div><div class='question-body'>



In order for us to accurately estimate mediation effects, a few conditions have to be met. One of the biggest is that of **no confounding.**

An unmeasured variable that is a common cause of both X and Y will bias the total and direct effects, and one that is a common cause of both X and M will bias the indirect effect (it will bias the X$\rightarrow$M path). Randomised experiments (i.e. randomly allocating people to different values of X) will avoid this, because nothing but the random allocation would cause X. However, confounding of the indirect effect can also happen if some variable is a common cause of both M and Y, and it is hard to randomly allocate to a mediator^[there _are_ methods that attempt to "block" a mediator, or to manipulate X in multiple ways in order to increase or decrease the mediators' effect. If you're interested see [*Design approaches to experimental mediation*, Pirlott & MacKinnon 2016](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jesp.2015.09.012){target="_blank"}].  

Can you think of two unmeasured variables that could be in the place of the variables indicated by `?` in @fig-blanks and may be confounding our estimates.  




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![fill in the blanks!](images/path_educ_conf_blank.png){#fig-blanks fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::







</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div class="solution-begin"><button id='sol-start-5' class="jk-circle-right solution-icon clickable" onclick="toggle_visibility('sol-body-5', 'sol-start-5')">  Solution </button></div><div class="solution-body" id = "sol-body-5" style="display: none;">



Here are my suggestions. Even if we don't believe that it _should_, something like "socioeconomic status" can likely influence both peoples' levels of education (people from wealthier backgrounds have more access to more years of education) and their eventual salary (social connections might lead to better paying jobs, etc.).  

Similarly, aspects of peoples' employment post-education will influence the skills they have _and_ their salary. For instance, some people might leave education and go into private industry jobs with lots of options for on-the-job training and 'upskilling'. This will lead to more skills, but could also lead to being promoted and therefore having a higher salary! 

![](images/path_educ_conf_example.png)



</div><p class="solution-end"></p>





<div class='question-begin'>Question 6</div><div class='question-body'>


Another assumption of our model here is that there is no "X-M interaction". By this, I mean that we are assuming that the effect of the mediator M on the outcome Y does not depend on the level of the predictor X.  

Think: what would an X-M interaction mean in this example?  



</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div class="solution-begin"><button id='sol-start-6' class="jk-circle-right solution-icon clickable" onclick="toggle_visibility('sol-body-6', 'sol-start-6')">  Solution </button></div><div class="solution-body" id = "sol-body-6" style="display: none;">




In our example of Educ$\rightarrow$Skill$\rightarrow$Salary, the "X-M interaction" would refer to the idea that the number of skills has a different effect on salaries depending on the level of education.  

Intuitively to me this actually seems like a pretty important possibility!  
Skills may well have a bigger bearing on salaries for people with lower levels of education. It's probably easier to think about this if we split Education into a binary thing. It's quite likely that in reality, there is an interaction like the picture below, where the number of skills tends to 'matter more' (i.e. lead to more of a difference in salaries) for people with less education.  




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](09ex_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::





</div><p class="solution-end"></p>


